So I saw the recent issue and commit that attempted to fix it, and notice that it could still be dangerous if users made a ~/storage a symlink to some directory before using the command, so I did a test:
```
$ mkdir /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir
$ touch /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir/a
$ mkdir /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir/b
$ touch /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir/b/c
$ ln -s /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir $HOME/storage
$ tree /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir
/data/data/com.termux/files/testdir
├── a
└── b
    └── c

1 directory, 2 files
$ termux-setup-storage
$ tree /data/data/com.termux/files/testdir
/data/data/com.termux/files/testdir
└── b
    └── c

1 directory, 1 file
$
```

It isn't as dangerous as I thought, but still you can see that files got deleted unexpectedly.

Tried to write something to do the task myself. Not heavily tested but seems to work. You can take it as a *reference*:
```
import java.io.File;
class recursiveDelete {
    static void deleteNoFollow(File file) {
	if (!file.delete()) {
	    File[] children = file.listFiles();
	    for (File child: children)
		deleteNoFollow(child);
	    file.delete();
	}
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
	File blah = new File(args[0]);
        deleteNoFollow(blah);
    }
}
```

P.S. I never get why would someone ever wanted/needed `termux-setup-storage` though. (I always uses the convenient `/sdcard` symlink that the system has for me; probably a bit trickier if one uses a real SD card though.)

